quic_parents_v2: My father and my mother have both been working full-time jobs since before they met, with my dad being a semiconductor engineer while my mom was a dentist, later starting her own dental business. They usually came home in the evening on weekdays, so either of my grandparents would usually be the one to take care of me until then. My parents were very focused on my academic success from a young age, so much so that my mental health deteriorated and I had a period of suicidal thoughts as young as in 8th grade. It also didn't help that they put me in a private school, so the expectation was that I wouldn't let the tuition costs go to waste. Throughout high school they also cared about my academics but started to let me become more independent about managing schoolwork and balancing extracurriculars. While they pushed for me to major in a STEM field for the profitability, I eventually convinced them to let me major in music technology as long as I minored in something that was reliable. Over the years, my parents have generally just been pretty strict about most things I do, though they've opened up more in recent years. However, they still have pretty conservative views; my mom pressured me to come out as bisexual, which she and my dad had a pretty negative reaction to. I still don't have the courage to tell them I'm trans and am not sure when I will have the courage. Right now, I'd say our relationship is a bit complicated, because while I'd like to separate myself from them and live independently, I also need their financial backing (which they thankfully have plenty of). It seems to be an either-or situation of living freely and independently versus having financial security, and right now I feel more comfortable taking the latter option.
